{
  "type": "feature",
  "title": "Improve SRS lapse handling: drop mature words further on failure",
  "description": "In app/dal/vocabulary.py, the `update_progress` function currently drops the SRS level by only 1 on an incorrect answer (`level = max(level - 1, 0)`). For mature words at level 4+ (14-60 day intervals), this is too lenient — a word at level 6 (60-day interval) that is forgotten drops to level 5 (30-day interval), meaning the user won't see it again for a month despite having just failed it. This is a well-known SRS anti-pattern.\n\nChange the lapse logic so that words at level 4 or above drop to level 2 (3-day review interval) on failure, while words at level 0-3 continue to drop by 1 as before. This matches the 'lapse' behavior in Anki and other proven SRS systems — a forgotten mature card needs to rebuild from short-term memory.\n\nSpecific changes:\n1. `app/dal/vocabulary.py` line ~166: Replace `level = max(level - 1, 0)` with: if level >= 4, set level = 2, else level = max(level - 1, 0). Add a constant `SRS_LAPSE_FLOOR = 2` for configurability.\n2. `tests/unit/test_vocabulary_dal.py`: Update `test_incorrect_at_max_level_drops` (line 325) to expect new_level == 2 instead of 5. Add new tests: `test_lapse_from_level_5_drops_to_2`, `test_lapse_from_level_4_drops_to_2`, `test_incorrect_at_level_3_drops_by_one` to verify the threshold behavior.\n3. `frontend/src/components/VocabSRSProgress.tsx`: Add a visual 'lapse' indicator when a word drops more than 1 level (e.g., show '⚡ Lapse' instead of just '↓'), helping users understand the bigger drop is intentional and beneficial.",
  "files_to_modify": ["app/dal/vocabulary.py", "tests/unit/test_vocabulary_dal.py", "frontend/src/components/VocabSRSProgress.tsx"],
  "priority": "medium",
  "estimated_complexity": "small"
}
